      "updated": 1766982882497,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "FB Post Search\n\nFunctional Requirement -\n   a. Users should be able to create and like posts\n   b. Users should be able to search posts by keyword\n   c. Users should be able to get search results sorted by recency or like count\n\nNon-Functional Requirements -\n   a. Latency to create and link Posts should be real time (< 100ms)\n   b. Search Latency should be real time (< 100ms)\n   c. The system should prioritize availability. It is okay if the number of likes is not uptodate\n   d. With 1B Active users, we can expect a read and write TPS of 15K\n   e. With 1T posts and each post being 1KB of data, total storage mounts to a Petabyte\n   f. The system should not have a single point of failure.\n\nAPI Contracts - \n\n1. POST /posts/ --> Returns PostId and status code\n   {\n       userId\n       title\n       text\n       timestamp\n       ..metadata\n   }\n\n2. POST /like/ --> confirmationId and status code\n    {\n         userId\n         postId\n         timestamp\n    }\n\n3. GET /search?query={}&sortedBy={Timestamp/Count}timestamp={}&last_post_id={}&count={}\n    List of \n    {\n        postId\n        title\n        text\n        authorId\n        creationtimestamp\n        lastModifiedTimestam\n    }\n\n\nHigh Level Design\n\n1. Users should be able to create and like posts\n     a. The App makes the request to 'Post' microservice to create a post and the microservice makes a DB call to insert a new record to the POST table.\n     b. Now, if another user makes a POST request to like that specific post, their app makes a request to 'LIKE' microservice to like a post and increment\n         the totalLikes column of the Post and add that raw information to the LIKE table.\n     c. Remember the LIKE table will have more writes as compared to POST table\n\n2. Users should be able to search posts by keyword\n      a. App1 will make a request to 'Search' microservice which will scan the entire POST table using 'LIKE %s' on the title and text column.\n      b. With 1T posts, this database call will be inefficient or may even timeout.\n      c. So, initially, we can start with top 50 results and return to the App.\n      d. App needs to be proactive in sensing that the user has completed its scroll and send a request to fetch the next 50 and so on.\n\n3. Users should be able to get search results sorted by recency or like count\n     a. Similarly App1 will make the request to Search microservice to provide the top50 results sorted by TotalLikes or creation timestamp.\n     b. App needs to be proactive in sensing that the user has completed its scroll and send a request to fetch the next 50 and so on.\n\n4. How can we scale the keyword search to support trillions of posts?\n     a. Remember we are not allowed to use Elastic Search, so we need to design an infrastructure with inverted indexes.\n     b. Creating inverted indexes is a long running task and need not block anything. So, whenever, a post is added to the DB, we \n        can request the DB to add it to the queue, where Lambda can process at its own speed by tokenizing and stemming the post\n        and then persisting those information in a Key/Value Pair disk database with O(1) access\n     c. We are basically mimicking the Lucene Algorithm.\n     d. Now, when a user makes a request, the Search microservice will fetch from the DB with inverted Indexes and not the main DB\n     e. The 'Value' is a Set which needs to be ordered. Now the ordering is of 2 types - (1) timestamp and (2) TotalLikes\n     f. For every word, we can also append a suffix which is word_likes and word_timestamp and the lambda would push the \n        post to both the varieties of the same word. \n    g. Since the Set is sorted, addition of a post would require the set to rebalance themselves (RBT). \n    h. If I had to sort the posts both by likes and timestamp, I would have a third category called word itself which will have posts\n        in sorted order.\n    i. If there are 1 Trillion posts, I don't need to sort all of them. For a user to get results, the user might be satisfied with 1000-10K results.\n    j. In such cases, I can limit by Ordered Set to be max of 1000 size.\n    k. So, now every key in the new DB will have a max of 1000 Post metadata.\n    l. I am referring metadata as id, title, text, userId which combines to be 1KB at max. So, every key will be at max of 1-2MB.\n\n5. How will the system handle queries with multiple keywords (e.g. \"taylor AND swift\")?\n     a. Initially, the microservice can start with querying 1 word at a time and then aggregate and sort them in memory.\n     b. However, sorting 2000 posts for 2 keywords is near real time. However, if you keep on adding multiple words, the list will soon increase\n         and we will miss the SLA of 100ms.\n     c.Since this is an AND operation, the SEARCH can effectively find the intersection between those lists and then sort them in memory.\n     d. So, the worst case could be sorting 1000 posts even though with increase in the number of keywords.\n\n6. How will the system handle queries with common keywords (e.g. \"the AND and\")?\n     a. Common words such as 'the' and 'and' are very frequent in all documents. Hence, they should be queried last.\n     b. The system can have a list of such words to maintain priority for searching.\n     c. So, when N keywords are provided and say X of them are common words, we will first query N-X and have \n         the intersection ready.\n     d. Post that we would query the and and and see if any of the results intersect with the previous intersection.\n     e. Remember since every value has max size of 1000, max intersection would be 1000 posts.\n     f. So, now the microservice can sort those 1000.\n\n7. What if the keywords are hot ?\n     a. If the keywords are hot, the database would be a bottleneck.\n     b. Since this is purely about read throughput, we would cache popular keywords (such as Taylor) in Redis to avoid hitting the database.\n     c. If there is a cache miss, we would read from DB (non-hot keywords)\n     d. If there is a mixture of hot and non-hot keywords, we will retrieve hot from cache and non-hot from DB and perform the intersection and then sort them\n     e. However, we need to proactively update the cache TTL depending upon the hotness of the keyword.\n     f. If a viral post is edited or a new viral post is added,  the cache needs to be refreshed and we can have something like cache versioning of the hot keyword\n     g. We would proceed with Redis <hot_keyword_versionNo>:SortedSet<Posts>\n\n8. How can we make ingestion scalable and fast with millions of posts and billions of likes?\n      a. I believe LIKE microservice would be hammered more than POST microservice.\n      b. Additionally, not all posts will receive the same amount of likes. Moreover, we don't need precise like count to perform sorting in the new DB with inverted indexes.\n      c. Since we called out eventual consistency in the requirements, lets take a wiggle room of 30 seconds to gather the likes and then persist them in the DB.\n      d. This will reduce the load on the database. The periodicity of 30 seconds is also very frequent. \n      e. Imagine Taylor Swift and Ariana Grande posts are viral and they differ from the third by a huge number.\n      f. Not updating likes for 30 seconds or even a minute wouldn't change anything.\n      g. IF there is a race between those two posts, they can be sorted after a minute also.\n      h. I think the main bottlneck would be LIKE microservice not hammering the DB and take a path of batching the write requests.\n      i. Kinesis/Flink can be sharded by post_id \n\n\n9. Walk me through how your Flink aggregator would handle the batching of likes over that 30-second window. \n    Specifically, how would it aggregate likes per post and what would trigger the batch write to update the inverted indexes?\n      a. Viral Post are being liked by multiple users and their app hammers the LIKE microservice. The LIKE microservice\n          persists the data in Kinesis which has a throughput of 1GB/sec, given that we are talking about billion of likes with each like being 1 KB.\n      b. The Flink aggregates those link in a tumbling window of 1 minute or 30 seconds. Once the window period is over, it makes a call to the database \n          to update TotalLikes = previousLikes + newCount\n      c. This triggers a database update which gets added to SQS and Lambda processes it and finds the same key word and add it to the same words. \n      d. For category LIKE, as soon as the post is inserted with new count, the previous records gets overriden and the sorted set keeps them on the top\n          or move to the second based on new like count.\n      e. Since Kinesis is shard by post_id, all the likes would likely fall on the same shard. Now, Flink as a consumer to Kinesis shard will collect all the likes\n          from the same post in its own shard, aggregate it in a fixed window and write it to the DB.\n     f. Even though Kinesis creates more shard to handle the hot post, we need a single Flink Aggregator to be a consumer to all the kinesis shards which are\n        consuming the same post so that it can aggreate all the likes for the same post.\n\n10. How can we optimize the storage requirements of the system?\n      a. With 1T posts and each post being 1KB of data, total storage mounts to a Petabyte\n      b. With likes, consider the storage amount to be Exabyte.\n      c. I would like to divide my tables into different databases as USER table is less likely hit, POST table is usually hit but LIKE table is most hit.\n      d. Hence, POST and LIKE table can reside in different databases.\n      e. Each of the databases can be sharded based on post_id to divide the write load as well as storage database.\n      f. Since SQS and Lambda does not have a state based on the problem, they can be attached to all the shards of the database. \n     g. Since we are sharding the databases, we should constantly migrate cold data to newer racks so that when new data gets added, the IOPS isn't increased.\n          If all new data lands on a rack, IOPS will be exhausted even though storage space will still there. Hence, always migrate cold data to reduce IOPS load.\n     h. The new DB with inverted indexes has a max limit per key of 1000. However, we can be smarter and start pruning old keywords\n         which haven't been queried.\n     i. We can have a ranking metrics on the keywords being actively queries upon. Every day, we can run some cron jobs which would eliminate rare\n        keywords from inverted index DB.\n     j. If the user queries that same keyword, lambda will have to construct again and insert them in the DB.\n     k. Or we can have 2 steps of pruning - we can mark something dead but do not remove it - this is marked for pruning but if a search requests\n        comes, we immediately query them and mark them as active.\n\n\n\n",
